If I were to write a C to Lean transpiler targeting a simple subset of C and using Clang, how might that be structured. Think hard, don’t word vomit 

Thought for a couple of seconds
A sane structure is not “C AST → Lean syntax” directly. Use Clang only as the front-end, then lower into your own tiny verified-ish IR, then print Lean.

C source
  ↓
Clang parse/typecheck
  ↓
Clang AST visitor
  ↓
Your C subset IR
  ↓
Normalization/desugaring
  ↓
Lean backend
  ↓
Lean file + proof/axiom boundary
1. Define the C subset first
Be restrictive. For v1:

int/uint/bool
structs without bitfields
arrays with fixed size
pointers only if disciplined
if/while/for
local variables
pure-ish functions
no goto
no setjmp
no volatile
no undefined behavior tolerated
no unspecified evaluation-order dependence
The important move: reject C programs that depend on C weirdness. Your transpiler should be a validator + translator, not a heroic C semantics engine.

2. Use Clang for parsing and semantic facts
Use LibTooling or a Clang plugin.

Walk:

RecursiveASTVisitor<MyVisitor>
Extract:

FunctionDecl
VarDecl
ParmVarDecl
RecordDecl
IntegerLiteral
DeclRefExpr
BinaryOperator
UnaryOperator
CallExpr
IfStmt
WhileStmt
ForStmt
ReturnStmt
CompoundStmt
But do not emit Lean here. Build your own IR.

3. Lower to a small C-like IR
Example:

type Ty =
  | I32 | U32 | Bool
  | Ptr Ty
  | Array Nat Ty
  | Struct Name

type Expr =
  | Var Name
  | Int Integer
  | Bool Bool
  | Bin Op Expr Expr
  | Un Op Expr
  | Call Name [Expr]
  | Load Expr
  | Field Expr FieldName
  | Index Expr Expr

type Stmt =
  | Let Name Ty Expr?
  | Assign LValue Expr
  | If Expr [Stmt] [Stmt]
  | While Expr [Stmt]
  | Return Expr
This IR is where you enforce:

types are supported
integer widths are known
lvalues are clean
no bad casts
no pointer arithmetic unless explicitly modeled
no UB-prone constructs
4. Normalize imperative C before Lean
Lean is happiest if you don’t emit raw imperative spaghetti.

Lower loops and mutation into one of two targets:

Option A: Lean do notation with StateM
Good for preserving C shape.

structure State where
  x : Int
  y : Int

def f : StateM State Int := do
  let mut i := 0
  while i < 10 do
    i := i + 1
  return i
This is operational and easy to generate.

Option B: Pure recursive functions
Better for verification.

int sum(int n) {
  int acc = 0;
  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) acc += i;
  return acc;
}
becomes roughly:

partial def sum.loop (n i acc : Int) : Int :=
  if i < n then
    sum.loop n (i + 1) (acc + i)
  else
    acc

def sum (n : Int) : Int :=
  sum.loop n 0 0
For serious Lean, avoid partial by emitting a fuel argument or requiring a decreasing measure.

5. Treat memory as a design decision
This is the central fork.

For a simple useful subset, I’d start with no raw memory model:

C local scalar variables → Lean locals/state fields
C structs → Lean structures
C arrays → Lean Array or Vector
C pointers → rejected, except maybe pointer-to-local lowered as reference-like lvalue
Later, add a memory model:

structure Mem where
  bytes : Std.HashMap Addr UInt8
But once you support arbitrary pointers, you are no longer writing a cute transpiler. You are writing a C semantics.

6. Integer semantics: pick explicitly
Do not casually map C int to Lean Int.

Choices:

C mathematical subset: require no overflow, emit Lean Int/Nat
C machine subset: emit UInt32/Int32-style bitvectors
For a transpiler that preserves execution, use fixed-width types.

For a transpiler meant for reasoning, use Int plus generated preconditions:

requires -2147483648 ≤ x + y ∧ x + y ≤ 2147483647
7. Backend layout
Emit one Lean module per C file:

import Std

namespace Transpiled.Foo

structure Point where
  x : Int
  y : Int

def add (x y : Int) : Int :=
  x + y

end Transpiled.Foo
For unsupported constructs, fail with a source span from Clang.

8. Practical implementation shape
clang-tool/
  main.cpp
  AstToIr.cpp
  SubsetChecker.cpp
  TypeLowering.cpp
  ExprLowering.cpp
  StmtLowering.cpp

ir/
  Ir.hpp

lean-backend/
  PrettyPrinter.cpp
  NameMangler.cpp
  LeanSyntax.cpp
Pipeline:

for each FunctionDecl:
  if not in subset: diagnostic
  irFn = lowerFunction(decl)
  irFn = normalize(irFn)
  lean = emitLean(irFn)
9. What I would build first
Target this subset:

pure functions
ints/bools
if/else
local lets
return
simple arithmetic
no loops initially
no pointers initially
Then add, in order:

structs
arrays
loops with fuel or partial
bounded integer semantics
simple pointer/reference idioms
The core design principle: Clang understands C; your IR understands your subset; Lean backend should be dumb.


A memory access in Clight is not lowered to bytes immediately. The generated Rocq AST still looks like C lvalues—globals, dereference, field selection—but the semantics interprets those through CompCert’s block/offset memory model.

Thought for 17s
Your example should be typed more like:

struct Object {
    int timer;
    int other;
};

struct Object *gObjects[10];

void setTimer(int i) {
    gObjects[i]->timer = 0;
}
clightgen would emit Rocq/Coq code morally like this:

Definition t_struct_Object :=
  Tstruct _Object noattr.

Definition f_setTimer := {|
  fn_return := tvoid;
  fn_callconv := cc_default;
  fn_params := ((_i, tint) :: nil);
  fn_vars := nil;
  fn_temps := nil;

  fn_body :=
    Sassign
      (* left-hand side: gObjects[i]->timer *)
      (Efield
        (Ederef
          (* gObjects[i] *)
          (Ederef
            (Ebinop Oadd
              (Evar _gObjects (tarray (tptr t_struct_Object) 10))
              (Etempvar _i tint)
              (tptr (tptr t_struct_Object)))
            (tptr t_struct_Object))
          t_struct_Object)
        _timer
        tint)

      (* right-hand side: 0 *)
      (Econst_int (Int.repr 0) tint)
|}.
The exact emitted syntax may differ slightly by CompCert version, but this is the conceptual shape.

The C expression:

gObjects[i]->timer = 0;
is represented approximately as:

gObjects[i]->timer
=
(*(gObjects + i))->timer
=
(*(*(gObjects + i))).timer
So there are two memory-relevant steps:

1. Load object pointer from gObjects[i].
2. Store 0 into that object's timer field.
In CompCert/Rocq memory semantics, globals and heap objects are not raw machine addresses. They are represented as blocks plus byte offsets.

A pointer value looks like:

Vptr block offset
So at runtime you might have:

gObjects global symbol ↦ block b_gObjects

gObjects[3] contains pointer:
  Vptr b_obj17 Ptrofs.zero

timer field of object 17 lives at:
  block b_obj17, offset field_offset(timer)
Then executing:

gObjects[3]->timer = 0;
means roughly:

load pointer-sized value from:
  b_gObjects + 3 * sizeof(pointer)

suppose it returns:
  Vptr b_obj17 0

store integer 0 at:
  b_obj17 + offset_of(timer)
In VST, you would usually describe the starting memory with separation-logic predicates. Very roughly:

SEP (
  data_at Ews
    (tarray (tptr t_struct_Object) 10)
    object_pointer_values
    (gv _gObjects);

  data_at Ews
    t_struct_Object
    object_i_contents
    obj_ptr
)
Where:

gv _gObjects
is the address of the global gObjects, and obj_ptr is the pointer stored at gObjects[i].

A spec for setTimer might say:

Definition setTimer_spec :=
 DECLARE _setTimer
 WITH i : Z,
      objects : list val,
      obj_ptr : val,
      obj_contents : reptype t_struct_Object,
      gv : globals
 PRE [ tint ]
   PROP (
     0 <= i < 10;
     Znth i objects = obj_ptr
   )
   PARAMS (Vint (Int.repr i))
   GLOBALS (gv)
   SEP (
     data_at Ews
       (tarray (tptr t_struct_Object) 10)
       objects
       (gv _gObjects);

     data_at Ews
       t_struct_Object
       obj_contents
       obj_ptr
   )
 POST [ tvoid ]
   PROP ()
   RETURN ()
   SEP (
     data_at Ews
       (tarray (tptr t_struct_Object) 10)
       objects
       (gv _gObjects);

     data_at Ews
       t_struct_Object
       (object_with_timer obj_contents 0)
       obj_ptr
   ).
That spec says:

Before:
  gObjects is an array of 10 object pointers.
  i is in bounds.
  gObjects[i] = obj_ptr.
  obj_ptr points to a valid Object struct.

After:
  same global object array.
  same object, except timer field is now 0.
So the memory proof is not “magical symbolic execution of C pointers.” You explicitly give the verifier a memory layout:

this global array exists
this index is in bounds
this slot contains this pointer
this pointer owns a struct Object
this field can be written
Then VST/CompCert semantics justify that the generated Clight assignment performs the corresponding load and store.


how do you give a "name" to, say, gObjects[10], and manipulate it in proofs later? for example proving that because foobar() is never called, gObjects[10] can never equal QUX

I’ll answer this at two levels: the low-level Clight/VST memory name, and the higher-level abstract state name you actually want for “slot 10 is never QUX.”

Thought for 13s
You give it two “names,” at two different abstraction levels.

At the Clight level, gObjects[10] is not a name. It is an lvalue expression:

(* morally: gObjects[10] *)
Definition e_gObjects_10 : expr :=
  Ederef
    (Ebinop Oadd
      (Evar _gObjects (tarray (tptr t_struct_Object) NUM_OBJECTS))
      (Econst_int (Int.repr 10) tint)
      (tptr (tptr t_struct_Object)))
    (tptr t_struct_Object).
CompCert Clight expressions include Evar, Etempvar, Ederef, Efield, etc.; assignments are statements over such expressions, not expression-level side effects. 

But in proofs, you usually do not want to manipulate that expression directly. You give the memory region a logical name.

For example, suppose C has:

struct Object *gObjects[240];

void foobar(void) {
    gObjects[10] = QUX;
}
In VST-ish proof style, you might describe the whole global array with a Coq variable:

WITH objs : list val,
     gv : globals
PRE []
  PROP (Zlength objs = 240)
  GLOBALS (gv)
  SEP (
    data_at Ews
      (tarray (tptr t_struct_Object) 240)
      objs
      (gv _gObjects)
  )
Here:

objs
is the proof-level name for the contents of the C global array, and:

Znth 10 objs
is the proof-level name for gObjects[10].

So the assertion:

gObjects[10] is not QUX
becomes something like:

Znth 10 objs <> gv _QUX
or, depending on whether QUX is a global object, enum, sentinel pointer, etc.:

Znth 10 objs <> Vptr b_qux Ptrofs.zero
VST uses predicates such as data_at to describe C memory objects in separation logic; the usual workflow is to run clightgen and then write verification files importing VST’s proof automation. 

Now, the key point:

foobar is never called
by itself is not enough to prove:

gObjects[10] can never equal QUX
unless you also prove a frame/no-write fact:

the only code capable of writing QUX into gObjects[10] is foobar
Otherwise some other code could do:

gObjects[10] = QUX;
or:

struct Object **p = &gObjects[10];
*p = QUX;
or:

memcpy(gObjects + 10, &QUX, sizeof QUX);
or mutate it through an alias.

The theorem you really want has this shape:

Theorem slot10_never_qux :
  forall tr objs0 objs_final,
    initial_state_has_gObjects objs0 ->
    Znth 10 objs0 <> qux_ptr ->

    execution_of_program prog tr ->
    starts_with_gObjects tr objs0 ->
    ends_with_gObjects tr objs_final ->

    foobar_unreachable prog ->
    only_foobar_writes_qux_to_gObjects10 prog ->

    Znth 10 objs_final <> qux_ptr.
For your preferred “no SM64 hardcoding” story, you would not hand-write only_foobar_writes_qux_to_gObjects10. You would derive it with a generic analysis over the generated Clight AST.

A plausible pipeline:

generated Clight program
  ↓
generic call graph analysis
  proves foobar unreachable
  ↓
generic write-target analysis
  finds all writes to gObjects[10]
  ↓
generic value-flow / assignment analysis
  proves no reachable write stores QUX there
  ↓
theorem
  slot 10 never equals QUX
The generated proof artifact might look like:

Definition writes_to_gObjects10 : list write_site :=
  collect_writes_to_global_array prog _gObjects 10.

Definition reachable_fns : list ident :=
  reachable_functions prog _main.

Example foobar_unreachable :
  reachable reachable_call_graph _main _foobar = false.
Proof.
  native_compute; reflexivity.
Qed.

Example no_reachable_qux_write_to_slot10 :
  no_reachable_write_of_value
    prog reachable_fns _gObjects 10 qux_ptr = true.
Proof.
  native_compute; reflexivity.
Qed.

Theorem gObjects10_never_qux :
  semantic_never_equals prog _gObjects 10 qux_ptr.
Proof.
  apply no_reachable_write_of_value_sound.
  exact no_reachable_qux_write_to_slot10.
Qed.
The hard part is making collect_writes_to_global_array sound.

For easy C, it handles direct writes:

gObjects[10] = QUX;
gObjects[i] = QUX;       // maybe if analysis can prove i = 10 or maybe conservatively unknown
For harder C, it must conservatively handle aliases:

p = &gObjects[10];
*p = QUX;
So your analyzer should return one of three results:

Inductive AnalysisResult :=
| ProvenNoWrite
| ProvenWriteSites of list write_site
| UnknownDueToAliasOrIndirectWrite.
Then your theorem only fires on ProvenNoWrite or on a fully accounted set of reachable write sites.

The important conceptual split is:

Clight name:
  _gObjects plus an lvalue expression for index 10

Proof name:
  objs : list val
  Znth 10 objs

Semantic fact:
  every reachable store preserves Znth 10 objs <> QUX
That is the right shape for Mario-land. You want generated facts like “no reachable Clight store can write this value to this abstract location,” not hand-written reasoning about every object slot.




