Someone is saying something about how it’s apparently hard to prove almost anything about loops currently, can you deeply look into this 

I’ll check what “hard to prove loops” means in this ecosystem: VST loop invariants, CompCert/Clight loop semantics, automation limits, and whether the difficulty is fundamental or just workflow.

Thought for 31s
The claim is basically right if they mean VST-style source verification. It is less true for your proposed “generic analyzer over generated Clight AST” approach.

The distinction matters.

What is hard about loops in VST
In VST, proving through a loop usually requires supplying a loop invariant manually. The VST manual is explicit: for while (E) C, you use forward-while Q, where Q is the loop invariant; for for loops there are specialized tactics, but still invariant-shaped data is required. The manual says proofs through if, while, and for need extra information such as join postconditions and loop invariants. 

For a while, VST generates four obligations:

1. precondition implies loop invariant
2. loop condition is safe to evaluate
3. loop body preserves loop invariant
4. invariant + loop exit condition implies the post-loop state
That is directly from the VST manual. 

So for:

for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    if (i == 12) bad();
}
the obvious human invariant is:

0 <= i <= 10
Then i == 12 is impossible. But VST generally will not just infer that for you and prove the whole thing automatically. You tell it the invariant, then prove the generated proof obligations.

For SM64-sized code, that is painful because loops often maintain nontrivial state:

object list traversal
surface list traversal
collision loops
input/demo loops
behavior script interpretation
area/node graph traversal
array scans with early exits
while loops over linked lists
Each such loop may need a custom invariant describing list shape, object validity, bounds, aliasing, and which globals are preserved.

That is what “loops are hard” usually means.

But your analyzer approach changes the problem
You are not primarily trying to write one VST proof per SM64 function. You want:

SM64 C
→ clightgen
→ Clight AST
→ generic analyzer
→ generic soundness proof
→ generated facts
In that world, loops become a static-analysis problem, not a hand-VST-invariant problem.

Clight itself represents C loops uniformly. In CompCert Clight, while, do while, and for are derived forms over a primitive Sloop; the Clight docs say the three C loops are replaced by one infinite-loop form Sloop s1 s2, with break and continue handled by continuations. 

So the generated AST does not hide loops. They appear as finite syntax with cycles in the control-flow relation.

What is easy despite loops
Some facts are still easy.

Direct call graph
For:

void x(void) {
    while (1) {
        y();
    }
}
you can still syntactically collect:

x directly calls y
No invariant needed.

Conservative reachability
If your analyzer says:

inside this function, every syntactic statement in a loop body is potentially reachable
then loops are no problem. You overapproximate.

This is useful for proving positive facts:

x may call y
this function contains a possible write to gObjects[10]
this function may call level_trigger_warp
But it is weak for negative facts.

Call graph non-reachability
If z has no direct calls, and there are no function-pointer complications, proving:

z does not call x
is easy even with loops elsewhere. A transitive call-graph search over a finite graph terminates regardless of source loops.

What is hard
The hard cases are value-sensitive negative facts.

Examples:

for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    if (i == 12) bad();
}
or:

while (obj != NULL) {
    if (obj->behavior == QUX) bad();
    obj = obj->next;
}
or:

for (i = 0; i < NUM_OBJECTS; i++) {
    if (gObjects[i] == QUX) bad();
}
To prove bad() unreachable, the analyzer must know something inductive:

i remains in [0, 10]
obj traverses only this list segment
gObjects[10] is never QUX
the loop does not corrupt the object list
this flag, once false, remains false until exit
That is the loop-invariant problem in another form. You can move it from “manual VST invariant” into “generic abstract interpreter invariant,” but it does not disappear.

The right approach for Mario-land
I would not start with VST loop proofs. I would build a certified or certifying Clight analyzer with a deliberately weak but useful abstract domain.

Something like:

Abstract value :=
  unknown
  | constant integer
  | interval [lo, hi]
  | finite set of enum values
  | pointer-to-global g
  | pointer-to-field base field
  | null/non-null
Then loops are handled by fixpoint iteration:

enter loop
  analyze body
  join result with loop head state
  repeat until stable
This is ordinary abstract interpretation.

CompCert already contains infrastructure in this general area: its development includes Kildall-style fixpoint solving and value/alias analyses used for compiler optimizations. The CompCert docs list Kildall for dataflow inequations and ValueAnalysis / ValueDomain for value and alias analysis. 

You probably would not use those modules unchanged for your SM64 theorem, but they show the ecosystem already has the right mathematical machinery.

Example: proving a loop path unreachable
C:

void f(void) {
    int i;
    for (i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        if (i == 12) {
            bad();
        }
    }
}
A generic interval analyzer proves:

at loop head: i ∈ [0, 10]
inside body after guard i < 10: i ∈ [0, 9]
therefore i == 12 is false
therefore bad() unreachable
The Rocq theorem shape:

Theorem interval_analyzer_sound :
  forall prog fn label state,
    analyze prog fn = Some facts ->
    facts_say_unreachable facts label = true ->
    ~ semantically_reaches_label prog fn label.
Then the generated proof for this file is just:

Example f_never_calls_bad :
  facts_say_unreachable (analyze example_prog _f) bad_label = true.
Proof.
  native_compute; reflexivity.
Qed.

Theorem f_never_calls_bad_semantic :
  ~ semantically_reaches_label example_prog _f bad_label.
Proof.
  eapply interval_analyzer_sound.
  exact f_never_calls_bad.
Qed.
That is the shape you want.

Where this breaks down
A simple interval/set analyzer handles:

bounded for loops
enum-like state machines
simple counters
flags
constant array indices
some switch dispatch
some direct global writes
It struggles with:

pointer aliases
function pointers
linked object lists
floating-point physics
arrays indexed by values not statically bounded
writes through unknown pointers
memcpy/memset-style mutation
behavior script interpreters
For those, the analyzer must either become more sophisticated or return:

Unknown
That is acceptable. The key is to make the analyzer soundly conservative:

Proven unreachable  => actually unreachable
Unknown             => no theorem
Never:

Unknown but pretend unreachable
How this relates to Start-button lower bound
The full game loop is literally loop-heavy. You do not want to prove:

main game loop terminates with cake ending only after Start
That is a nightmare.

A better theorem is local and safety-shaped:

Within the title/demo/menu transition code,
no path reaches transition T unless START_BUTTON appears in buttonPressed
or some explicitly modeled demo timeout path occurs.
Loops matter only insofar as they update input state over frames. You would model the outer loop abstractly:

each frame:
  read_controller_inputs
  update state
Then prove an invariant over frames:

if no Start rising edge has occurred so far,
then title-start transition has not occurred,
except maybe demo-timeout transition if included.
That is an inductive invariant. It is not avoidable. But you can make it generic:

a certified state-machine extractor
+ a generic temporal safety checker
+ generated transition relation from Clight
Bottom line
The statement “loops are hard” is accurate for manual VST proofs and for semantic negative facts. VST does not remove the need for loop invariants; the manual workflow explicitly requires them. 

For your project, loops are not a fatal blocker, but they force the next design decision:

Do you want manual invariants?
  Use normal VST.

Do you want zero SM64 hardcoding?
  Build a generic abstract interpreter / model checker over Clight,
  prove it sound once, and accept Unknown for loops it cannot analyze.
I would start with a weak analyzer that handles bounded integer loops and direct calls/writes. That is enough to get real Mario-land proof artifacts without drowning immediately in object-list invariants.




